aa(lp209
VLet me just give you one example that I think is incredibly simple, and I love.
p210
aVWe want to get people to be more energy efficient.
p211
aVWhy? It cuts fuel poverty, it cuts their bills,
p212
aVand it cuts carbon emissions at the same time.
p213
aVHow do you do it?
p214
aVWell, we've had government information campaigns over the years
p215
aVwhen they tell you to switch off the lights when you leave the home.
p216
aVWe even had \u2014 one government minister once told us to
p217
aVbrush our teeth in the dark.
p218
aVI don't think they lasted very long.
p219
aVLook at what this does. This is a simple piece of behavioral economics.
p220
aVThe best way to get someone to cut their electricity bill
p221
aVis to show them their own spending,
p222
aVto show them what their neighbors are spending,
p223
aVand then show what an energy conscious neighbor is spending.
p224
aVThat sort of behavioral economics
p225
aVcan transform people's behavior
p226
aVin a way that all the bullying and all the information
p227
aVand all the badgering from a government cannot possibly achieve.
